AB  - The proceedings contain 33 papers. The special focus in this conference is on Fundamentals of Computation Theory. The topics include: Automata and program analysis; a tour of recent results on word transducers; some results of zoltan esik on regular languages; contextuality in multipartite pseudo-telepathy graph games; generalized satisfiability problems via operator assignments; new results on routing via matchings on graphs; energy-efficient fast delivery by mobile agents; parameterized aspects of triangle enumeration; testing polynomial equivalence by scaling matrices; token jumping in minor-closed classes; expressive power of evolving neural networks working on infinite input streams; minimal absent words in a sliding window and applications to on-line pattern matching; subquadratic non-adaptive threshold group testing; FO model checking on map graphs; multiple context-free tree grammars and multi-component tree adjoining grammars; decidable weighted expressions with presburger combinators; the complexity of routing with few collisions; parikh image of pushdown automata; tropical combinatorial nullstellensatz and fewnomials testing; on weak-space complexity over complex numbers; deterministic oblivious local broadcast in the SINR mode; undecidability of the lambek calculus with subexponential and bracket modalities; decision problems for subclasses of rational relations over finite and infinite words; listing all fixed-length simple cycles in sparse graphs in optimal time; reliable communication via semilattice properties of partial knowledge; polynomial-time algorithms for the subset feedback vertex set problem on interval graphs and permutation graphs; determinism and computational power of real measurement-based quantum computation and busy beaver scores and alphabet size.
