TI  - Formation of S-Cl phosphorothioate adduct radicals in dsDNA S-oligomers: Hole transfer to guanine vs disulfide anion radical formation
PY  - 2013
T2  - Journal of the American Chemical Society
VL  - 135
IS  - 34
SP  - 12827
EP  - 12838
DO  - 10.1021/ja406121x
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-84883277560&doi=10.1021%2fja406121x&partnerID=40&md5=effb98c86f53010aadf047445d532951
AB  - In phosphorothioate-containing dsDNA oligomers (S-oligomers), one of the two nonbridging oxygen atoms in the phosphate moiety of the sugar-phosphate backbone is replaced by sulfur. In this work, electron spin resonance (ESR) studies of one-electron oxidation of several S-oligomers by Cl2 •- at low temperatures are performed. Electrophilic addition of Cl2•- to phosphorothioate with elimination of Cl - leads to the formation of a two-center three-electron σ2σ*1-bonded adduct radical (-P-S-ÌCl). In AT S-oligomers with multiple phosphorothioates, i.e., d[ATATAsTsAsT]2, -P-S-ÌCl reacts with a neighboring phosphorothioate to form the σ2σ*1- bonded disulfide anion radical ([-P-S-ÌS-P-]-). With AT S-oligomers with a single phosphorothioate, i.e., d[ATTTAsAAT]2, reduced levels of conversion of -P-S-ÌCl to [-P-S-ÌS-P-] - are found. For guanine-containing S-oligomers containing one phosphorothioate, -P-S-ÌCl results in one-electron oxidation of guanine base but not of A, C, or T, thereby leading to selective hole transfer to G. The redox potential of -P-S-ÌCl is thus higher than that of G but is lower than those of A, C, and T. Spectral assignments to -P-S-ÌCl and [-P-S-ÌS-P-]- are based on reaction of Cl2 •- with the model compound diisopropyl phosphorothioate. The results found for d[TGCGsCsGCGCA]2 suggest that [-P-S-ÌS-P-] - undergoes electron transfer to the one-electron-oxidized G, healing the base but producing a cyclic disulfide-bonded backbone with a substantial bond strength (50 kcal/mol). Formation of -P-S-ÌCl and its conversion to [-P-S-ÌS-P-]- are found to be unaffected by O2, and this is supported by the theoretically calculated electron affinities and reduction potentials of [-P-S-S-P-] and O2. © 2013 American Chemical Society.
