AB  - The chemical shift dispersion in ultrahigh field and 2D-nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy can be used to study the structure-property relationships of important polymers. The pulsed field gradient (PFG) 2D-heteronuclear multiple quantum coherence (HMQC) and heteronuclear multiple-bond correlation (HMBC) experiments provide improved resonance assignments for poly(ethylene-co-1-octene). The high-temperature PFG probe extends the use of PFG HMQC and HMBC 2D experiments to high-melting or low-solubility polymers and materials which must be heated to increase mobility.
